We’ll be honest: predicting anything in AI is like trying to nail Jell-O to a wall. But what’s clear heading into 2026 is that AI is no longer an experiment. It’s embedded in workflows, powering decisions, and quietly rewriting the boundaries of what organizations can, and must, secure.

## Agentic AI: Expanding Both Capabilities and Risk

Despite the hype, agentic AI—systems that take actions—is still early in real enterprise adoption. However, 2026 is poised to shift this trajectory. As tooling stabilizes and governance frameworks mature, agentic AI will move from scattered pilots to structured deployments.

{% callout type="caution" %}
**Autonomy Cuts Both Ways**: Misconfiguration or compromise can introduce entirely new attack pathways. Agents can magnify impact, make mistakes at machine speed, or take actions no one realized they had permission to execute.
{% /callout %}

## The Emerging Threat of Data Poisoning

With more enterprises training and fine-tuning models, data poisoning is set to move from an “interesting security talk-track” to something the industry actually needs to take seriously.

Poisoned data has a way of slipping into the mix quietly and reshaping how a model behaves. It might introduce bias, hide signals, or shift decisions. The challenge is that poisoned data looks like everything else.

## The Evolution of Cyber Threats

We expect to see the first wave of **fully autonomous intrusion attempts**. These AI agents will be capable of performing reconnaissance, exploiting vulnerabilities, and exfiltrating data at a pace no traditional security tool is prepared for.

> "We’ll see fully autonomous, AI-driven cyberattacks become the new norm." — *Itamar Golan, CEO of Prompt Security*

## Advances Toward AGI: Progress, Pressure, and Practical Realities

Will 2026 deliver AGI? Probably not.
But it will deliver models that behave far more independently than anything we have used before. They will reason across tasks, take initiative, and operate with context that increasingly resembles human-level decision flow.

That progress brings governance pressure. As models become more capable, the risks tied to autonomy, misalignment, and unintended behavior also grow.

Here’s to a steady, secure, and well-governed 2026.
